{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2531"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2531"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.2,0.46,0.13,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103454"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2531"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2531"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1328"},{"type":"tags","id":"2044"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36747"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103454"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic two weeks after noticing a lump in her left breast. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm firm, irregular mass in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast with no skin changes or axillary lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA follow-up mammography shows an irregular mass with microcalcifications. A core biopsy confirms the proliferation of cells that invades the basement membrane. A CT scan of the abdomen and thorax finds no evidence of distant metastases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe breast tumour is human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2) positive, and oestrogen receptor (ER) and progesterone receptor (PR) negative. Her last menstrual period was 15 years ago. Adjuvant therapy is considered as part of her treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following adverse events is she most at risk of with the likely intended adjuvant treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vaginal dryness","Osteoporosis","Dilated cardiomyopathy","Endometrial cancer","Thromboembolism"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient has HER2 positive, ER/PR negative breast cancer, making \u003Cstrong\u003Etrastuzumab (Herceptin)\u003C/strong\u003E the appropriate adjuvant therapy. It is a humanised monoclonal antibody against the HER2 tyrosine kinase receptor which inhibits the proliferation of tumour cells that over-express HER2. Trastuzumab also activates an immune response that lyses tumour cells. Trastuzumab should be avoided in patients with cardiac dysfunction and/or elderly patients with increased risk of cardiac dysfunction as it may increase the risk of cardiotoxicity. One of the adverse effects of trastuzumab is \u003Cstrong\u003Edilated cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E. Regular cardiac monitoring is required during trastuzumab therapy due to the risk of cardiotoxicity, which can manifest as dilated cardiomyopathy with reduced left ventricular ejection fraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThromboembolism\u003C/strong\u003E such as deep vein thrombosis and pulmonary embolism, as well as \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial cancer\u003C/strong\u003E, are more common in patients on \u003Cstrong\u003Etamoxifen\u003C/strong\u003E - an adjuvant therapy used for biopsy-proven, oestrogen hormone-receptor sensitive breast cancer. It is an oestrogen receptor antagonist that decreases breast tumour growth in ER positive tumours. This medication is contraindicated in women with a history of thrombosis. It is prone to drug-drug interactions, thus consideration must be given to CYP enzyme inhibitors and inducers which may impact efficacy and toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn increased risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoporosis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Evaginal dryness\u003C/strong\u003E are side effects of \u003Cstrong\u003Earomatase inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E, an adjuvant therapy for biopsy-proven, oestrogen receptor sensitive breast cancers in postmenopausal women. They work by reducing the conversion of androstenedione to oestrone and decreasing the conversion of testosterone to oestradiol, thereby decreasing tumour growth. An important point to note is that this adjuvant therapy is only appropriate for postmenopausal women and is contraindicated in premenopausal women as they can induce ovulation. It is also ineffective in premenopausal women as it does not inhibit the majority of oestrogen secretion from the ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dilated cardiomyopathy is an important side effect of trastuzumab therapy for HER2 positive breast cancer.","Trastuzumab is used as adjuvant therapy for HER2 positive breast cancer.","Cardiac monitoring is required during trastuzumab therapy due to the risk of cardiotoxicity."],"references":["Fi\u00faza M. Cardiotoxicity associated with trastuzumab treatment of HER2+ breast cancer. Adv Ther. 2009 Jul;26 Suppl 1:S9-17. doi: 10.1007/s12325-009-0048-z. Epub 2009 Jul 24. PMID: 19669637. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19669637/","Giordano SH, Temin S, Chandarlapaty S, Crews JR, Esteva FJ, Kirshner JJ, Krop IE, Levinson J, Lin NU, Modi S, Patt DA, Perlmutter J, Ramakrishna N, Winer EP, Davidson NE. Systemic Therapy for Patients With Advanced Human Epidermal Growth Factor Receptor 2-Positive Breast Cancer: ASCO Clinical Practice Guideline Update. J Clin Oncol. 2018 Sep 10;36(26):2736-2740. doi: 10.1200/JCO.2018.79.2697. Epub 2018 Jun 25. PMID: 29939838. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29939838/","Geisler J, Haynes B, Anker G, Dowsett M, L\u00f8nning PE. Influence of letrozole and anastrozole on total body aromatization and plasma estrogen levels in postmenopausal breast cancer patients evaluated in a randomized, cross-over study. J Clin Oncol. 2002 Feb 1;20(3):751-7. doi: 10.1200/JCO.2002.20.3.751. PMID: 11821457. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11821457/","Slamon D, Eiermann W, Robert N, Pienkowski T, Martin M, Press M, Mackey J, Glaspy J, Chan A, Pawlicki M, Pinter T, Valero V, Liu MC, Sauter G, von Minckwitz G, Visco F, Bee V, Buyse M, Bendahmane B, Tabah-Fisch I, Lindsay MA, Riva A, Crown J; Breast Cancer International Research Group. Adjuvant trastuzumab in HER2-positive breast cancer. N Engl J Med. 2011 Oct 6;365(14):1273-83. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa0910383. PMID: 21991949; PMCID: PMC3268553. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21991949/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2531"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T17:14:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T17:15:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2531"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"1034